2020-03-25 09:47:54-05:00,Wireless tools tracking the spread of the coronavirus could stoke consumers' fears of privacy overreach,"Mass surveillance appears to be among the most effective tools to combat the spread of the coronavirus, but by sharing detailed location data with governments, wireless carriers could be setting a long-term precedent that alienates consumers. In South Korea, SK Telecom launched a real-time location-tracking tool that police can use to identify and break up large gatherings. In China, the government has mandated the adoption of smartphone software to track citizens' health, which determines their access to public spaces. Since South Korea and China have been two of the most effective countries in containing domestic outbreaks, many other governments — including in Austria, Israel , Russia , the UK, and the US — have petitioned domestic wireless carriers to help institute similar programs. This presents a double-bind for wireless carriers, as helping create a near-term public health tool will also amplify consumer privacy concerns. In the US, wireless carriers have thus far demonstrated a willingness to break operational norms to combat the pandemic.",VZ,en,Business Insider
